      {
        "id": 3904103,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-09-30T04:39:09.907Z",
        "cooked": "<p>It\u2019s from vines in the commune of Puligny, which I believe were acquired from Chartron, but I\u2019m not sure about that. So deep soils vs the stony, sloping Sous Ch\u00e2talet for d\u2019Auvenay, and a sunnier exposition vs the north-east exposition of the latter. Viticulture is the same, but winemaking is quite different: the Domaine Leroy version is, as I understand it, fermented and matured in tank; whereas the d\u2019Auvenay Aligot\u00e9 is in 100% new oak.</p>",
